{{short description|Ancient Greek city in Crimea}} {{Infobox ancient site |name = Panticapaeum |native_name = Παντικάπαιον {{in lang|grc}} |alternate_name = |image = Архітектурно-археологічний комплекс «Стародавнє місто Пантікапей».JPG |alt = |caption = The [[prytaneion]] of Panticapaeum, second century BC. [[Kerch]]'s Obelisk of Glory is visible in the background. |map_type = Crimea |map_alt = |map_size = 270 |coordinates = {{coord|45|21|3|N|36|28|7|E|display=inline,title}} |location = [[Kerch]], [[Crimea|Autonomous Republic of Crimea]] |region = [[Taurica]] |type = Settlement |part_of = |length = |width = |area = {{convert|100|ha|abbr=on}} |height = |builder = Settlers from [[Miletus]] |material = |built = 7th or 6th century BC |abandoned = Approximately 370&nbsp;AD |epochs = [[Archaic Greece|Archaic Greek]] |cultures = [[Greeks|Greek]] |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = |archaeologists = |condition = Ruined |ownership = Public |management = |public_access = Yes |website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> |notes = }}
'''Panticapaeum''' ({{lang-grc|Παντικάπαιον|Padikápeon}}) was an [[Ancient Greece|ancient Greek]] city on the eastern shore of [[Crimea]], which the Greeks called [[Taurica]]. The city was built on [[Mount Mithridat]], a hill on the western side of the [[Strait of Kerch|Cimmerian Bosporus]]. It was [[Greeks in pre-Roman Crimea|founded]] by [[Miletus|Milesians]] in the late 7th or early 6th century BC. The ruins of the site are now located in the modern city [[Kerch]].
==Early existence== [[File:ThracianCoin.JPG|thumb|A coin from Panticapaeum, bearing a star inside a [[diadem]] and the letters "ΠΑΝ", 2nd century BC.]] {{see also|Greeks in pre-Roman Crimea}} During the first centuries of the city's existence, imported Greek articles predominated: [[pottery]] (see [[Kerch Style]]), [[terracotta]]s, and metal objects, probably from workshops in [[Rhodes]], [[Corinth]], [[Samos]], and [[Athens]]. Local production, imitated from the models, was carried on at the same time. Athens manufactured a special type of bowl for the city, known as [[Kerch]] ware. Local potters imitated the [[Hellenistic]] bowls known as the [[Gnathia]] style as well as relief wares—[[Megara|Megarian]] bowls. The city minted silver coins from the 5th century BC and gold and bronze coins from the 4th century BC.<ref>Sear, David R. (1978). ''Greek Coins and Their Values ''. Volume I: Europe (pp. 168-169). Seaby Ltd., London. {{ISBN|0 900652 46 2}}</ref> At its greatest extent it occupied {{convert|100|ha}}.<ref name=encyuk /> The [[Hermitage Museum|Hermitage]] and [[Kerch]] Museums contain material from the site, which is still being excavated.
[[File:Pan compilation.jpg|thumb|left|300px| Representations of Pan on 4th century BC gold and silver Pantikapaion coins]]
==Fifth to first centuries BC== In the 5th–4th centuries BC, the city became the residence first of the [[Archaeanactids]] and then of the [[Spartocids]], dynasties of [[Thracian]] kings of [[Bosporan Kingdom|Bosporus]], and was hence itself sometimes called Bosporus. Its economic decline in the 4th–3rd centuries BC was the result of the [[Sarmatians|Sarmatian]] conquest of the steppes and the growing competition of [[Ancient Egypt|Egyptian]] grain.
===Mithridates=== [[File:Scythians shooting with bows Kertch antique Panticapeum Ukrainia 4th century BCE.jpg|thumb|Small statue of [[Scythians]] with bows from Panticapeum, fourth century BC.]]{{Off topic|date=November 2019}} The last of the [[Spartocids]], [[Paerisades V]], apparently left his realm to [[Mithridates VI]] Eupator, king of [[Kingdom of Pontus|Pontus]]. This transition was arranged by one of Mithridates's generals, [[Diophantus (general)|Diophantus]], who earlier had been sent to Taurica to help local Greek cities against [[Palacus]] of [[Lesser Scythia]]. The mission did not go smoothly: Paerisades was murdered by [[Scythians]] led by [[Saumacus]], and Diophantus escaped to return later with reinforcements to suppress the revolt (c. 110&nbsp;BC).
Half of a century later, Mithridates took his life in Panticapaeum, when, after his defeat in a [[Third Mithridatic War|war]] against [[Ancient Rome|Rome]], his son and heir [[Pharnaces II of Pontus|Pharnaces]] and citizens of Panticapaeum turned against him.
